<section xml:id="sec-topology-of-the-real-numbers">
  <title>Topology of the real numbers</title>

  <objectives>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Understand metrics and how they formalize the idea of distance on a set.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Use key properties of the absolute value function, especially the triangle inequality.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Describe and prove properties of open and closed sets.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </objectives>
  
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Introduction goes here.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        A metric on a set <m>X</m> is a function <m>d:X\times X\to\bb R</m> that satisfies the following properties:
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Positive definite: <m>d(x,y)\ge 0</m> for all <m>x,y\in X</m>, and <m>d(x,y)=0</m> if and only if <m>x=y</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Symmetric: <m>d(x,y)=d(y,x)</m> for all <m>x,y\in X</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Triangle inequality: <m>d(x,y)+d(y,z)\ge d(x,z)</m> for all <m>x,y,z\in X</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        The absolute value can be used as a distance function: <m>d(x,y)=|x-y|</m>.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Other corollaries of the triangle inequality:
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>|x+y|\le |x|+|y|</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\big||x|-|y|\big|\le|x-y|</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Extended: <m>\big||x|-|y|\big|\le|x\pm y|\le |x|+|y|</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        A set <m>U\subseteq\bb R</m> is open if, for every <m>x\in U</m>, there exists <m>\delta >0</m> such that <m>(x-\delta,x+\delta)\subseteq U</m>.
        We call <m>(x-\delta,x+\delta)</m> the <m>\delta</m>-neighborhood of <m>x</m> and denote it <m>V_{\delta}(x)</m>, so <m>V_{\delta}(x)\subseteq U</m>.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Open sets are closed under arbitrary units and finite intersections.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Every open set is a countable union of disjoint open intervals.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        A set is closed if its complement is open.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        De Morganâ€™s laws for open and closed sets
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</section>
